			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2016</a> paper:</span><br><i>Efficient Development of Consistent Projectional Editors using Grammar Cells</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/MarkusVölter.html">Markus Völter</a>, <a href="../profile/TamásSzabó.html">Tamás Szabó</a>, <a href="../profile/SaschaLisson.html">Sascha Lisson</a>, <a href="../profile/BerndKolb.html">Bernd Kolb</a>, <a href="../profile/SebastianErdweg.html">Sebastian Erdweg</a>, <a href="../profile/ThorstenBerger.html">Thorsten Berger</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/2997364.2997365">10.1145/2997364.2997365</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagM">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> It presents methods and infrastructure for building projectional editors—core language workbench technology.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> Grammar cells enable modular composition of editor definitions across language fragments.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5h.html"><span class="tagL">T5H: Usability</span></a><ul><li> A central goal is improving usability/consistency of projectional editors for developers.
</li></ul></li></ul>
